    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 52,
    "last_activity_date" : 1326963886,
    "creation_date" : 1326963886,
    "answer_id" : 8923414,
    "question_id" : 8923398,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>[a-z]</code> matches a <strong>single</strong> char between a and z. So, if your string was just <code>\"d\"</code>, for example, then it would have matched and been printed out. </p>\n\n<p>You need to change your regex to <code>[a-z]+</code> to match one or more chars. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "user_type" : "does_not_exist",
      "display_name" : "user647772"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1326963946,
    "creation_date" : 1326963946,
    "answer_id" : 8923419,
    "question_id" : 8923398,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Your regular expression <code>[a-z]</code> doesn't match <code>dkoe</code> since it only matches Strings of lenght 1. Use something like <code>[a-z]+</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
