      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "What do you mean by <i>other languages followed suit</i>? From what I know, only C++ has an equivalent set of methods - <code>regex_search</code> and <code>regex_match</code>. In Python, <code>re.match</code> only anchors the match at the start of the string (as if it were <code>\\Apattern</code>) and Python 3.x has got a nice <code>.fullmatch()</code> method. In JS, Go, PHP and .NET, the there are no regex methods that anchor the match implicitly. ElasticSearch, XML Schema and HTML5/Validators Angluar patterns  are always anchored by default. In Swift/Objective C, there is a way to anchor the pattern at the start with an option."
