    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Welcome to Java's misnamed <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#matches-java.lang.String-\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>.matches()</code></a> method... It tries and matches ALL the input. Unfortunately, other languages have followed suit :(</p>\n<p>If you want to see if the regex matches an input text, use a <code>Pattern</code>, a <code>Matcher</code> and the <code>.find()</code> method of the matcher:</p>\n<pre><code>Pattern p = Pattern.compile(&quot;[a-z]&quot;);\nMatcher m = p.matcher(inputstring);\nif (m.find())\n    // match\n</code></pre>\n<p>If what you want is indeed to see if an input only has lowercase letters, you can use <code>.matches()</code>, but you need to match one or more characters: append a <code>+</code> to your character class, as in <code>[a-z]+</code>. Or use <code>^[a-z]+$</code> and <code>.find()</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
